"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425410","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Government remains committed to the Cancer Drugs Fund and is working with NHS England and the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence on the future arrangements for the Fund.</p><br /><p>NHS England has advised that its plans for a public consultation on its proposals for the Fund are being finalised.</p><br /> <br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","14299","2015-11-10T13:09:15.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425410/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425410/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans for the public consultation on the Cancer Drugs Fund to begin.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","14354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425411","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>The MenB immunisation programme was introduced in September 2015, with the vaccine being offered to babies at 2, 4 and at 12 months of age. The vaccine is also available for the small number of older children who are at increased risk of infection, such as those with specific immune problems.</p><br /><p>The Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisatio (JCVI) carried out a comprehensive and careful review of a wide range of evidence in relation to MenB vaccine and did not recommend the use of MenB vaccine in other age groups, including older children.</p><br /><p>The Department, in collaboration with the JCVI and Public Health England, has identified that preparatory research is needed before the effects of MenB carriage in adolescents can be addressed. This preparatory research is in the process of being contracted and it is hoped that this work will begin in early 2016.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-05T16:54:14.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425411/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425411/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Meningitis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the meningitis B vaccine will be available for children and young people; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","14390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425412","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>We are advised by NHS England that it is working with its co-commissioning clinical commissioning groups to assess the requirements of the new development utilising the existing infrastructure and the requirements for an estimated population of in excess of 30,000 over a 10 year plus timeframe.</p><br /><p>We understand that new models of delivery of primary care services are being investigated with an estimate of around 15 additional general practitioners required to serve the final population numbers.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-05T15:25:06.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425412/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425412/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","General Practitioners: Battersea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of how many additional GPs will be needed to supply the Battersea-Nine Elms development; and how many such GPs are planned to be provided.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","14386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425413","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Government recognises the importance of supporting cancer survivors and is committed to working with the National Health Service, charities and patient groups to deliver the new Cancer Taskforce strategy.</p><br /><p>The report of the independent Cancer Taskforce, Achieving World-Class Cancer Outcomes: A Strategy for England 2015-2020 (July 2015), states that we need to transform our approach to support people living with and beyond cancer. The strategy notes that depression in cancer patients can be treated by medication and by psychological treatment. These treatments are most effectively and efficiently delivered using a systematic collaborative care model, such as Depression Care for People with Cancer. Cancer Taskforce strategy recommends accelerating the roll-out of the Recovery Package that includes a needs assessment that may lead to a patient being referred to support services that include psychological support. The Cancer Taskforce report says that the aim should be that by 2020 every person with cancer will have access to elements of the Recovery Package.</p><br /><p>We are working with the NHS, charities and patient groups to implement the independent Cancer Taskforce’s recommendations.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-10T17:39:22.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425413/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425413/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Stem Cells: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the benefits of psychological support for (a) patients who have received and (b) the families of patients who have received a stem cell transplant.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","14267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425414","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>Our offer on a new contract for junior doctors includes transitional arrangements that guarantee that all junior doctors currently working legal hours will not receive a pay cut compared to their current contract. Those in the higher stages of training will remain on current pay terms; for those moving onto the new pay terms, we are offering pay protection.</p><br /><p>Around 1% of junior doctors currently work on rotas that have breached the current limits on hours, and these junior doctors receive Band 3 payments (100% of basic salary). New contractual safeguards will include stronger limits on hours and patterns of work; and there will be stronger contractual processes, with external scrutiny, for dealing with variations from planned working. These Band 3 payments will not, therefore, apply or be protected.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-10T17:54:50.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425414/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425414/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Junior Doctors: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will ensure that junior doctors do not suffer a reduction in pay as a result of the Government's proposals to change junior doctors' contracts.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","14327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425415","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>Neither the Department nor Health Education England hold the information requested in the format specified. To collate the data would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-05T16:41:58.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425415/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425415/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Doctors: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of the doctors entering core and further specialty training were in each (a) specialty and (b) training region or deanery in each year since 2005.","true","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","14322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425416","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>The UK Foundation Programme Office collects data and produces reports annually on behalf of Health Education England and the devolved nations which show next career destinations of second year foundation doctors who have successfully completed their foundation training across the United Kingdom.</p><br /><p>Data prior to 2011 was not routinely collected by the UK Foundation Programme Office. Data from the 2015 destination survey is not yet available.</p><br /><p>The numbers provided in the attached table are from responses to a survey of outgoing F2 doctors and not all doctors provide a response. The appointments to specialty /general practice (ST/GP) are self-declared by the doctors in response to the survey and are not verified against recruitment data.</p><br /><p>Whilst the survey is a fairly accurate predictor of the destination of doctors who have completed foundation training the figures are not intended to be an accurate employment record.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-05T17:00:55.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425416/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425416/answer","Specialty general practice training 2011-14.docx","Specialty general practice training 2011-14.docx","Specialty/general practice training 2011-14","Specialty/general practice training 2011-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425416/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Doctors: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of doctors left foundation training and entered training posts in core or specialty training in each year between 2008 and 2015.","true","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","14323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425417","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>The latest monthly workforce statistics for July 2015 which are published by the Health and Social Care Information Centre show that there are 1,005 full-time equivalent gastroenterologist consultants currently employed in the National Health Service in England.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-05T15:23:17.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425417/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425417/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Gastrointestinal System: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many permanent gastroenterologist consultants are currently employed in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","14311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425418","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>The deadline for clinical commission groups to submit their Local Transformation Plans was Friday 16 October, and plans were submitted covering all local areas. These plans are currently being assured by NHS England’s regional assurance teams and this is intended to be completed during November.</p><br /><p>The £30 million NHS England allocated to clinical commissioning groups for improving children and young people’s eating disorders is intended to be spent in 2015-16.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-05T15:26:48.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425418/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425418/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Eating Disorders: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 28 October 2015 to Question 13212, by when the assurance of clinical commissioning groups' (CCG) local transformation plans by NHS England's regional teams are planned to be completed; and whether he plans that the additional £30 million that has been allocated to CCGs will be spent in full in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","14464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425419","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>NHS Employers will conduct a full impact assessment once the final proposals are developed.</p><br /><p>Individual employers are also obliged under equalities legislation to ensure all their staff receive equal pay for work of equal value, which the new contract proposals will support by linking pay increases to responsibility.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-05T16:45:57.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425419/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425419/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Junior Doctors: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what equality impact assessment his Department has carried out on its proposals to reform the junior doctor contract.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","14463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425420","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>Public Health England (PHE), NHS England and the National Offender Management Service commission individual health and wellbeing needs assessments (HNAs) in all prisons and young offender institutions in England on a regular basis, as part of the commissioning timetable. The current NHS England procurement timetable runs to 2017 and the current round of HNAs are commissioned to inform this.</p><br /><p>In the procurement process for prison health services, an HNA identifies health needs for which health services will becommissioned in that establishment. All prisons have produced individual HNAs and these are now at various stages of review. NHS England anticipates that each prison would need to undertake a full HNA every three to five years and to complete a low level refresh of its HNA every year. HNAs are not currently published routinely, but some are published by PHE’s regional Public Health Observatories, with details of these available at:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.apho.org.uk/default.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.apho.org.uk/default.aspx</a></p><br /><p>All HNAs are available on request from the local NHS England Area Team commissioners.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-05T15:01:01.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425420/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425420/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Prisoners: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2015 to Question 7476, when he expects Public Health England and the National Offender Management Services' health needs assessment of all prisons to be (a) complete and (b) published.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","14465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425421","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>The latest referral to treatment waiting times published by NHS England on 8 October 2015 shows there were just over 3.3 million people waiting to start consultant-led treatment at the end of August 2015.</p><br /><p>In 2013/14, there were 1.3 million more operations compared with 2009/10.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-10T12:51:41.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425421/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425421/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Hospitals: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people are currently on an NHS referral to treatment waiting list.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","14439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425422","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>Health Education England has responsibility for commissioning training for the National Health Service workforce and for working with NHS organisations to ensuretheright numbersof midwives are available to deliver the recommendations of the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidelines, published 27 February 2015, which includes the need for every woman to have at least one registered midwife present during established labour.</p><br />","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-05T14:56:47.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425422/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425422/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","Midwives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will estimate the number of additional midwives that would be required to enable all women to receive one-to-one care from a midwife during labour.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","14419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425423","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>As part of the establishment of NHS Improvement in April 2016, Monitor and the NHS Trust Development Authority are aligning their quarterly reporting processes and will be publishing their reports together towards the end of the year.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-05T15:18:31.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425423/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425423/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","NHS: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects (a) Monitor and (b) the Trust Development Authority to publish their 2015-16 second quarter performance reports.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","14420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425424","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State outlined in his Written Ministerial Statement of 21 July 2015 (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-07-21/HCWS161/" target="_blank">HCWS161</a>), that £6.9 billion was saved through lower administration costs and has been reinvested in front line services in the last Parliament, with the Government achieving its target of reducing administration costs by a third.</p><br /><p>The saving figures are the reduction in the Department’s total administration costs against the baseline set out in the Impact Assessment for the Health and Social Care Act. They are measured at a macro level, so an itemised breakdown is not available.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-05T16:49:24.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425424/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425424/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will itemise savings made by the NHS that have been attributable to the provisions of the Health and Social Care Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","14421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425425","Cabinet Office","false","2015-11-06","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-11-06T13:40:47.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425425/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425425/answer","PQ 14411.pdf","PQ 14411.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Fatal Overdose","UKSA Letter to Member - Fatal Overdose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425425/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-02","Opiates: Overdoses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of fatal opioid overdoses in the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","14411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425426","Department of Health","false","2015-11-05","<p>Departmental officials were first notified of a project which was run between December 2014 and February 2015 in the south of England on 23 October 2015 by Monitor, the independent health sector regulator.</p><br /><p>We are advised that Monitor is taking action with South East Coast Ambulance Service Foundation Trust regarding concerns about the project and the regulator is working with the Trust now to identify the negative impact this project could have had on patients. It is Monitor’s function to undertaken such investigations independently of the Department where there are no immediate patient safety issues. Monitor and Departmental officials regularly discuss such issues on a routine basis.</p><br /><p>As part of regulatory action, Monitor advises it has asked the trust to carry out a detailed independent review of the impact the project had on patients. Monitor has asked the Trust to do this with the help of an external expert, who the regulator will select. The full details of what the review will look at and how long it will take are being worked on by the trust and Monitor, including consideration of publication of the review finding.</p><p>In March, NHS England convened a risk summit meeting involving all partners following the suspension by South East Coast Ambulance Service of their unofficial call-handling project. It was agreed that NHS England would undertake an external investigation. The report of the investigation was published by NHS England today and is attached.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","14423 ; 14424","2015-11-05T17:38:53.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425426/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425426/answer","151105 NHSE External Investigation re SECAmb 111 Call Management Partition Red 3 Green 5.pdf","151105 NHSE External Investigation re SECAmb 111 Call Management Partition Red 3 Green 5.pdf","NHS England South East Coast Ambulance Report","NHS England South East Coast Ambulance Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425426/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-02","South East Coast Ambulance Service NHS Foundation Trust: NHS 111","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he was made aware of the project undertaken by South East Coast Ambulance NHS Foundation Trust in winter 2014-15 relating to prioritisation of NHS 111 calls.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","14422"
