"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425486","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-05","<p>The Secretary of State announced on 25 June 2015 the pause of work on Midland Main Line electrification and TransPennine electrification. This was to avoid potentially abortive costs while work was carried out to replan the delivery of these projects. On 30 September 2015 work on these projects resumed.</p><br /><p>Other Network Rail Control Period 5 projects have been continuing while Sir Peter Hendy carries out his review.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-11-05T12:44:38.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425486/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425486/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-02","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 29 October 2015 to Question 13286, whether any additional projects have been paused but not announced by Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","14449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425487","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-05","<p>The government is tripling the capital investment in the Strategic Road Network. Highways England have been given responsibility for delivery of the Road Investment Strategy and operation of the network.</p><br /><p>A four year term contract was tendered competitively by Highways England to a consortium consisting of CH2M Hill, Mace and PwC (CMP) in early July 2015 to help provide additional support to improve their capability and available resources to deliver an increasingly demanding and complex programme.</p><br /><p>This has no impact on the role, responsibilities and requirements of Highways England.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","14425 ; 14426","2015-11-05T16:21:12.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425487/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425487/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-02","Highways England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what framework of work Highways England is negotiating with the CH2M Hill/Mace/PwC consortium.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","14446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425488","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-05","<p>The Department and Network Rail are updating business cases as part of the Hendy Review Process. Network Rail is continuing to examine the deliverability and potential scheduling of Great Western works following which the benefit cost ratio for the programme will be updated.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-11-05T12:51:58.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425488/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425488/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-02","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2015 to Question 4759, if he will update the benefit-cost ratio for Great Western electrification given in that Answer to reflect the revised cost estimate for that electrification project confirmed in oral evidence by Mark Carne of the Committee of Public Accounts, on Network Rail: planning and delivery of 2014-19 rail investment programme, HC473, Q1, on 21 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","14462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425489","Wales Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>My Ministerial team and I have regular discussions with the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change on numerous subjects, including the proposed Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon.</p><p>This could be an exciting project with potential to open the door to possible future tidal investment in other areas of Wales, but we need to ensure that the scheme is both affordable and value for money. The Government is currently in the first phase of a Contract for Difference negotiation with the developer of the proposed project. This process of due diligence will enable us to gain a better understanding of the project, including detailed scrutiny of its costs, timescales and potential benefits.</p><br />","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2015-11-09T15:41:12.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425489/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425489/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-02","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change on the proposed Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","14435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425490","Wales Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>There has been no stationery reported lost or stolen from the Wales Office in the last five fiscal years.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2015-11-09T16:29:31.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425490/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425490/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-02","Wales Office: Stationery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what estimate he has made of the value of stationery that has been (a) lost and (b) stolen from his Department in each of the last five fiscal years; and what the cost was of replacing such stationery.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","14378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425491","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-09","<p>This information is not available, as there is no central record kept of lost or stolen stationery.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-11-09T15:20:19.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425491/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425491/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Stationery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the value of stationery that has been (a) lost and (b) stolen from his Department in each of the last five fiscal years; and what the cost was of replacing such stationery.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","14379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425492","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-05","<p>We expect to be able to form a reliable estimate once a significant proportion of working-age Disability Living Allowance recipients have been reassessed for the Personal Independence Payment. Over 1.75 million claimants require reassessing; as of July 2015 circa 186,900 had been reassessed.</p><br /><p>As referenced in our previous reply of 16 September 2015, DWP will continue to pay DLA for four weeks after the decision not to pay PIP enhanced mobility component is made. The Motability charity has confirmed that claimants can keep their car for up to three weeks after DLA payments end. This means that claimants will retain their car for up to nearly two months even though they are not entitled to PIP enhanced mobility component.</p><br /><p>In addition, the Department has worked closely with Motability to ensure that those claimants who no longer meet the criteria for the Motability Scheme are supported through the transitional period. For most of these claimants who entered into their first lease agreement with Motability before January 2013, Motability will provide transitional support of £2,000. This will enable many claimants to continue to meet their mobility needs by purchasing a used car. For claimants who entered into their first lease agreement with the scheme after January 2013 and up to December 2013, Motability will supply transitional support of £1,000 to assist with mobility costs.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-11-05T14:53:21.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425492/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425492/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-02","Personal Independence Payment: Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 16 September 2015 to the hon. Member for Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey to Question 9852, by when his Department will be able to form a reliable estimate of the number of disability living allowance recipients who are Motability users who will not qualify for the enhanced rate of the personal independence payment mobility component.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","14444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425493","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-05","<p>We are committed to supporting small and micro-businesses to adapt to their new automatic enrolment duties. Together with The Pensions Regulator, we have launched a new broadcast-led communications campaign to raise awareness of automatic enrolment amongst small employers.</p><p>The Pensions Regulator has also recently launched a new interactive and simplified online step by step guide to automatic enrolment, designed to meet the specific needs of employers who may not have pensions experience, including those with just one or two staff. Employers using the website can access tailored information relevant to their circumstances. The Pensions Regulator also provides online content for business advisers who play an important role in supporting smaller employers to meet their legal duties. To raise awareness and understanding, the Regulator has had over 500 meetings with intermediary firms and spoken at over 300 events around the UK during the last year</p><p>The Regulator sends a series of letters to every employer starting at least 12 months before their staging date, which is the date that the law applies to them. These letters set out what an employer needs to do and by when to comply with the law and signposts to the relevant information on the Regulator’s website.</p><p>To help employers adjust to the costs of automatic enrolment the minimum employer contribution level starts at 1% and increases gradually to 3% by October 2018. In addition, to ensure that all firms have access to quality, low-cost pension provision, The National Employment Savings Trust (NEST) was established by the Government and has a public service obligation to accept any employer that chooses NEST for automatic enrolment.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","14316","2015-11-05T15:05:46.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425493/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425493/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-02","Occupational Pensions: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure that small and medium-sized businesses are aware of their obligations relating to workplace pensions.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","14445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425494","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-05","<p>Jobcentre Plus Work Coaches regularly undertake outreach work in local communities. We have no specific knowledge of a welfare rights advisor working in a food bank in Birkenhead.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-11-05T15:44:05.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425494/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425494/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-02","Food Banks: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his oral evidence to the Work and Pensions Committee of 28 October 2015, for how long a welfare rights adviser has been placed in the Birkenhead food bank; and when he plans to roll-out the placement of such advisers to all food banks.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","14467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425495","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-06","<p>The First-tier Tribunal – Social Security and Child Support, administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS), hears appeals against Department for Work and Pensions’ decisions on a range of benefits.</p><br /><p>HMCTS is unable to provide the information requested as it is not held centrally.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","14288","2015-11-06T10:59:59.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425495/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425495/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-11-02","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average waiting time is for a disability benefit appeal to reach a tribunal; and what steps he is taking to reduce that average time.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","14287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425496","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-06","<p>The First-tier Tribunal – Social Security and Child Support, administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS), hears appeals against Department for Work and Pensions’ decisions on a range of benefits.</p><br /><p>HMCTS is unable to provide the information requested as it is not held centrally.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","14287","2015-11-06T10:59:59.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425496/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425496/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-11-02","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the average time it takes in Birmingham for a disability benefit appeal to reach a tribunal; and what assessment he has made of the effect of that average time on the financial position of appellants.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","14288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425497","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-10","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-11-10T14:28:39.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425497/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425497/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-02","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many delays to benefit payments there were in (a) Gloucester, (b) the South West and (c) England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","14329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425498","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-05","<p>We are committed to supporting small and micro-businesses to adapt to their new automatic enrolment duties. Together with The Pensions Regulator, we have launched a new broadcast-led communications campaign to raise awareness of automatic enrolment amongst small employers.</p><p>The Pensions Regulator has also recently launched a new interactive and simplified online step by step guide to automatic enrolment, designed to meet the specific needs of employers who may not have pensions experience, including those with just one or two staff. Employers using the website can access tailored information relevant to their circumstances. The Pensions Regulator also provides online content for business advisers who play an important role in supporting smaller employers to meet their legal duties. To raise awareness and understanding, the Regulator has had over 500 meetings with intermediary firms and spoken at over 300 events around the UK during the last year</p><p>The Regulator sends a series of letters to every employer starting at least 12 months before their staging date, which is the date that the law applies to them. These letters set out what an employer needs to do and by when to comply with the law and signposts to the relevant information on the Regulator’s website.</p><p>To help employers adjust to the costs of automatic enrolment the minimum employer contribution level starts at 1% and increases gradually to 3% by October 2018. In addition, to ensure that all firms have access to quality, low-cost pension provision, The National Employment Savings Trust (NEST) was established by the Government and has a public service obligation to accept any employer that chooses NEST for automatic enrolment.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","14445","2015-11-05T15:05:46.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425498/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425498/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-02","Occupational Pensions: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department has given to micro-businesses in adapting to new automatic enrolment pension schemes.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","14316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425499","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-05","<p>In 2010 the independent Making Automatic Enrolment Work (MAEW) review considered the impact of automatic enrolment on small and micro businesses. DWP’s impact assessments and on-going evaluation of Automatic Enrolment continue to monitor the costs and benefits of automatic enrolment on small businesses, including those with fewer than 10 employees.</p><br /><p>DWP’s evaluation reports and impact assessments are all available online.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-11-05T14:06:41.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425499/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425499/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-02","Occupational Pensions: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of his proposals for automatic enrolment of employees in pension schemes on businesses with fewer than 10 employees.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","14313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425689","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-05","<p>We have been open about the difference between real world and laboratory testing for diesel cars and our modelling takes into account the gap between laboratory testing and real world emissions. The UK government is committed to taking action on emissions testing. We see real world testing as the ultimate solution and a vital step in tackling air pollution. The vote to introduce RDE in 2017 is an important milestone but we will continue to press at EU level for a comprehensive approach to emissions testing to restore consumer confidence and deliver our wider air quality and climate objectives.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2015-11-05T16:38:40.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425689/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425689/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-02","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect on air quality of levels of emissions from motor vehicles.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart McDonald","902028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425690","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-05","<p>Defra launched the Great British Food campaign this week to promote food and drink entrepreneurs from across the UK at home and abroad.</p><p>Through the Food and Drink International Action Plan we have supported over 4,000 businesses and opened 130 new markets.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2015-11-05T16:03:12.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425690/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425690/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-02","Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to promote regional food and drink.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","902020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425770","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2015-11-05","<p>The Speaker's Committee is in regular dialogue with the Electoral Commission on matters concerning electoral fraud, most notably in advance of the Commission publishing its corporate plan on an annual basis.</p><br /><p>The Commission provides advice to those who are involved on the frontline in identifying, investigating and prosecuting cases of electoral fraud. Before each set of elections the Commission provides advice to the police, electoral administrators and others on ways to prevent and detect electoral fraud, based on the best practice it has identified through working with partners across electoral administration and the justice system. Each year the Commission publishes data on allegations of electoral fraud that are reported to the police.</p><br /><p>The Commission targets additional support for those on the front line in 18 areas in England where there is a higher risk of allegations of electoral fraud. This includes Slough and the Commission will be working again with these areas before the elections in May 2016 to build on what was done prior to the General Election. The Commission issued briefings to all honourable members in the last parliament on the work it was undertaking prior to the General Election to help tackle electoral fraud and will do so again before the elections in May 2016.</p><br /><p>In its 2014 review of electoral fraud, the Commission recommended that voters in Great Britain should be required to produce ID at polling stations, although it is yet to receive a response to this recommendation from the Government. The Commission has submitted evidence to the review being undertaken by Sir Eric Pickles and hopes that he agrees with it and that the Government accepts the Commission’s recommendation.</p><br />","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2015-11-05T10:14:30.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425770/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425770/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2015-11-02","Elections: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what discussions the Speaker's Committee has had on the extent of electoral fraud; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","902013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426371","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2015-11-05","<p><del class="ministerial">It is in everyone’s interest that all operators in the supply chain should receive a fair price for their goods. That means sharing the risk across the supply chain and I am pleased that some retailers already do this.</del></p><p><del class="ministerial">The EU Commission has listened to our calls for further action here and agreed to establish a new High Level Group to focus on a number of issues, including the relationship between farmers and retailers.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Government has introduced the Grocery Code Adjudicator to ensure fair dealing and we encourage supermarkets to offer contracts linked to production costs. In addition we pressed the EU to make available a support fund and the average farmer in England and Wales will receive a payment of around £1800 to ease the pressure on their cashflow.</ins></p><br /> <br />","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-11-05T16:55:25.873Z","2015-11-05T18:03:22.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426371/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426371/answer","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426371/answer/previousversion/27961","Biography information for George Eustice","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-02","Dairy Products: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she has taken to ensure that dairy farmers receive a fair and sustainable price for their produce.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","902032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426372","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2015-11-05","<p><del class="ministerial">We have established a programme of research to accurately assess our effectiveness, including a national framework for monitoring of pollinators. Over half of mid–tier applications to Countryside Stewardship contain the Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package. Monitoring and evaluation of the scheme makes provisions for assessing the impact on pollinators. The Implementation Plan sets out details on progress with the Strategy and will be published shortly.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">We have established a programme of research to accurately assess the effectiveness of our pollinator strategy. Over half of mid-tier applications to the new Countryside Stewardship scheme contain the Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package.</ins></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-11-05T16:57:06.453Z","2015-11-05T18:03:06.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426372/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426372/answer","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426372/answer/previousversion/27965","Biography information for George Eustice","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-02","Pollinators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the National Pollinator Strategy since its publication in November 2014.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","902034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425052","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-09","<p>In relation to SSI’s closure in Redcar, I expect the majority of the fund announced on 2 October to go towards supporting training of former SSI workers and those in the supply chain, helping businesses to grow and create jobs, and the future of the Tees Valley economy more broadly. We are working with the local Task Force, chaired by Amanda Skelton, to shape these proposals and in total, we have agreed over £40 million of support aimed at skills and jobs creation:</p><ul><li>£3 million has been made available to four Further Education colleges in the region to support re-training activity, as well as a further £2.65m skills funding to plug any gaps in skills provision not available via the Further Education Offer;</li><li>£1.7 million to ensure that the fifty apprentices who were with SSI can continue their apprenticeships with alternative employers;</li><li>A £16.5 million Jobs and Skills Fund to help local firms employ former SSI workers or their spouses in full-time or part-time jobs for a minimum of three years;</li><li>£16 million support for firms in the SSI supply chain and wider Tees Valley impacted by the Redcar steelworks closure, to safeguard jobs, provide the stimulus to create new posts and provide expert assistance to help them expand their business</li><li>£750,000 to fund advice and grants to start up a new business.</li></ul><p>In addition, we have announced a package, worth up to £9 million, jointly with Tata, to support Scunthorpe steelworkers, the local economy and supply chain. We are working closely with a local Task Force, chaired by my noble Friend Baroness Liz Redfern, to deliver this support.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-12-09T10:06:20.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425052/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425052/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-30","Iron and Steel: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what material and financial support his Department is providing to people made redundant in the steel industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","14187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425053","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-04","<p>Freezing the repayment threshold will not affect the cost of attending university. It will mean that students, once earning, will on average meet a greater share of these costs over their working life through loan repayments, helping ensure the long-term financial sustainability of the system. Lower earning graduates below the repayment threshold will not be affected by the proposed changes.</p><br /><p>Estimates of the impact of freezing the repayment thresholds are illustrated in the consultation document, which has been published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/freezing-the-student-loan-repayment-threshold" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/freezing-the-student-loan-repayment-threshold</a></p><br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-11-04T13:30:09.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425053/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425053/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-30","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Government's proposal to freeze the earnings threshold for plan 2 student loans on the cost of attending university.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","14204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425054","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-09","<p>The employment rate of young people who have left full-time education is 73.9% – its highest level in more than a decade and above the UK working age average. The rate for young people not in full-time education is the highest for over ten years</p><p><br>Over time participation in education has grown, and the majority of young people in full-time education are outside the labour force. The proportion of all young people who have left full-time education and are unemployed is 6.2% - below where it was before the recession and close to the lowest on record. The UK performs well internationally, with the fourth highest youth employment rate in the European Union.</p><p>The employment rate for young people fell during the recession and, as a result, unemployment rose. The EHRC report did not take full account of the recovery in the labour market, including the youth labour market that has since taken place.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","14203","2015-11-09T15:40:22.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425054/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425054/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-30","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the finding of the Equality and Human Rights Commission in its report, Is Britain Fairer, published in October 2015, that the employment gap between the oldest and youngest age groups has increased.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","14195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425055","Women and Equalities","false","2015-11-04","<p>The EHRC is an independent body, and its report ‘Is Britain Fairer?’ covers a five-year period 2008-13 across both the Labour and coalition governments. We welcome the positive areas of progress it refers to and note the challenges it raises. The information in the report will be used by the EHRC to help develop its next strategic plan, covering the period 2016-19.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","14196","2015-11-04T15:20:53.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425055/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425055/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2015-10-30","Graduates: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the finding of the Equality and Human Rights Commission in its report, Is Britain Fairer, published in October 2015, that there are persistent gender pay gaps among graduates.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","14197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425056","Women and Equalities","false","2015-11-04","<p>The EHRC is an independent body, and its report ‘Is Britain Fairer?’ covers a five-year period 2008-13 across both the Labour and coalition governments. We welcome the positive areas of progress it refers to and note the challenges it raises. The information in the report will be used by the EHRC to help develop its next strategic plan, covering the period 2016-19.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","14197","2015-11-04T15:20:53.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425056/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425056/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2015-10-30","Graduates: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the findings of the Equality and Human Rights Commission in its report, Is Britain Fairer, published in October 2015, that (a) there are persistent gender pay gaps among graduates and (b) employment and earnings premiums among graduates are lower for women than for men.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","14196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425057","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-12","<p>Since 2013 employment has risen by over a million people and the UK’s employment rate is at a record high. The Government is creating employment opportunities for all age groups. Since the first quarter of 2010, youth unemployment has fallen and 229,000 more young people are in employment.</p><p>Skills remain important for delivering better employment outcomes for younger workers. The lifetime benefits to apprentices are between £48,000 and £74,000 for Level 2 and between £77,000 and £117,000 for Level 3 Apprenticeships. The average graduate of higher education will earn over £100,000 more over their lifetime than a similar individual who completed their education with 2 or more A levels. The Government is therefore ensuring further and higher education providers are more responsive to the needs of employers, and that young people get the rights skills for the job market.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-12T14:14:35.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425057/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425057/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-30","Employment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the finding of the Equality and Human Rights Commission in its report, Is Britain Fairer, published in October 2015, that up to 2013 there was a decline in both earnings and full-time employment for younger workers, despite them being more likely to be better qualified than previous generations.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","14198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425058","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-09","<p>The employment rate of young people who have left full-time education is 73.9% – its highest level in more than a decade and above the UK working age average. The rate for young people not in full-time education is the highest for over ten years</p><p><br>Over time participation in education has grown, and the majority of young people in full-time education are outside the labour force. The proportion of all young people who have left full-time education and are unemployed is 6.2% - below where it was before the recession and close to the lowest on record. The UK performs well internationally, with the fourth highest youth employment rate in the European Union.</p><p>The employment rate for young people fell during the recession and, as a result, unemployment rose. The EHRC report did not take full account of the recovery in the labour market, including the youth labour market that has since taken place.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","14195","2015-11-09T15:40:22.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425058/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425058/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-30","Employment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 5.2 of the Equality and Human Rights Commission report, Is Britain Fairer, published October 2015, what steps he plans to take to address that report's conclusion that the employment rate for young people has fallen and the unemployment rate has risen, even accounting for increased participation in education.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","14203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425059","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-09","<p>The amount of centrally-provided capital funding provided to each further education college in each of the last five years is shown in the attached table.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-09T16:30:56.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425059/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425059/answer","FE College capital Grants 2010-11 to 2014-15.xls","FE College capital Grants 2010-11 to 2014-15.xls","Table of capital funding to FE colleges","Table of capital funding to FE colleges","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425059/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-30","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much centrally-provided capital funding has been provided to each further education college in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","14240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425060","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-12","<p>The Department has no plans to investigate companies which sell improperly trained dogs for disabled children. However, where consumers believe a company is giving misleading information or is in breach of legislation regarding sales to consumers, they should contact the Citizens Advice consumer helpline on 08454 04 05 06 (<a href="http://www.adviceguide.org.uk" target="_blank">www.adviceguide.org.uk</a>). The helpline offers a free service advising consumers on their rights and passes on details of complaints to Trading Standards Services where appropriate for further enforcement action.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-12T14:15:46.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425060/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425060/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-30","Guide Dogs: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to investigate companies which sell improperly trained dogs as special guide dogs for disabled children.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","14244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425061","Cabinet Office","false","2015-11-05","<p>The Major Project Portfolio for each Department is agreed by the Department, the Major Projects Authority and the relevant HM Treasury spending team. Each programme on the portfolio is subject to an agreed schedule of approvals and assurance, which will normally include Gateway Reviews. There is no provision for formal exemption.</p><p>A Project Assessment Review is conducted either instead of or in addition to Gateway Reviews, and allows for specific terms of reference to be tailored to meet the assurance needs of the particular Government Major Project.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","14169","2015-11-05T13:17:46.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425061/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425061/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425061/answer/previousversion/27854","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-30","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, in what circumstances major Government programmes are exempted from the requirement for Gateway Reviews.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","14168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425062","Cabinet Office","false","2015-11-05","<p>The Major Project Portfolio for each Department is agreed by the Department, the Major Projects Authority and the relevant HM Treasury spending team. Each programme on the portfolio is subject to an agreed schedule of approvals and assurance, which will normally include Gateway Reviews. There is no provision for formal exemption.</p><p>A Project Assessment Review is conducted either instead of or in addition to Gateway Reviews, and allows for specific terms of reference to be tailored to meet the assurance needs of the particular Government Major Project.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","14168","2015-11-05T13:17:46.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425062/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425062/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-30","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, in what circumstances major Government programmes are subjected to Project Assessment Reviews instead of Gateway Reviews; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","14169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425063","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>The government recognises the value of natural capital to the country’s long-term economic growth. We do not currently agree that an investment programme for natural capital should explicitly feature in the National Infrastructure Plan. We do, however, strive for all publically funded infrastructure investments to make a positive contribution to protecting and enhancing our natural environment. For example, the Roads Investment Strategy has ring-fenced £225 million in an Environment Fund and £75 million in an Air Quality Fund to ensure more is done to limit the impact of the Strategic Roads Network on the environment.</p><p>As specific decisions on spending allocations in this Parliament will be set out following the Spending Review later this month, I cannot yet comment on future investment in natural capital. However, the government takes natural capital very seriously. We have set long term-goals to stop the decades of decline in wildlife and habitats, and have already seen some improvements. Since 2010 we have helped to create over 150,000 acres of field margins, wetlands and woodlands, and woodland cover is at its highest level in 700 years.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-04T16:55:10.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425063/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425063/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Natural Resources","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will (a) incorporate natural capital into the national infrastructure plan, (b) take steps to ensure that new man-made infrastructure projects do not deplete the UK's natural capital asset base and (c) prioritise investment in natural capital.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","14161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425064","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-09","<p>In the summer, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) recruited 3,000 additional staff into customer facing teams. The recruitment process included bringing people in on contracts to work in the evenings and at weekends, thus building capacity to handle calls outside of normal working hours.</p><br /><p>HMRC have also implemented their biggest ever training programme, ensuring that customer support teams can move across a wide range of work according to customer demand.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-11-09T16:14:24.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425064/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Revenue and Customs: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent steps HM Revenue and Customs has taken to shorten waiting times for customers.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","14163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425065","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>HM Treasury regularly undertakes activities to monitor and assess key macroeconomic risks across all sectors of the economy, in line with current priorities.</p><p>The Treasury also feeds into the wider work on environmental risks that is undertaken across government: and in particular, through consideration of the analysis, advice and recommendations of the Natural Capital Committee which reports to the government, including HM Treasury, via the Economic Affairs Committee. The NCC’s work includes assessments of environmental trends and their impacts on the economy. The government’s response to the NCC’s third State of Natural Capital Report sets out how this work will be taken forward, including through the development of a 25 Year Environment Plan which will focus on those environmental assets that are most vulnerable to unsustainable use and where investment will deliver the greatest benefit.The Treasury is working closely with Defra to develop this plan.</p><p>Departments also work together on the UK contribution to the activities of the EU Raw Materials Initiative, which includes ongoing work that assesses and mitigates materials risks. Additionally, under the Climate Change Act 2008, the Government has a statutory role to produce, on a five-yearly cycle, an assessment of the risks and opportunities for the UK arising from climate change. Reporting under the Adaptation Reporting Power (as set out under the Climate Change Act), allows us to assess how key sectors are identifying risks from climate change and addressing them.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-04T16:51:48.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425065/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425065/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Natural Resources","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to assess, mitigate and monitor macro-economic risks associated with trends in (a) environmental degradation, (b) resource scarcity, (c) climate change and (d) other aspects of the natural environment.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","14156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425066","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>HM Treasury is working closely with Defra and other Government Departments on the development of the 25 Year Environment Plan. A cross-Government group, which includes Treasury officials, will ensure the Plan reflects the full breadth of relevant policy interests and levers that influence the environment.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-04T16:47:06.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425066/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425066/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Natural Resources","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what work his Department is undertaking to contribute to the development of the Government's 25 year plan for nature.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","14157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425067","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>Almost 2.4 million apprenticeship starts were delivered in the last Parliament and we will build on that success and deliver 3 million in this Parliament. We will introduce an apprenticeship levy to increase employer investment in apprenticeships. We are increasing the quality of apprenticeships through more rigorous assessment and grading at the end of the apprenticeship. The Enterprise Bill will protect the term ‘apprenticeship’ in law to prevent misuse. From next April, employers of apprentices under the age of 25 will no longer be required to pay National Insurance contributions for those employees.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-04T17:10:08.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425067/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425067/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Government's report, Fixing the Foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, Cm9098, published July 2015, what steps he has taken to increase the quantity and quality of apprenticeships in accordance with that report's recommendations.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425068","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>The Government will publish a Business Tax Roadmap by April 2016, setting out plans for business taxes over the rest of the parliament. This will give businesses the certainty they need to plan long-term investment.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-11-04T17:33:51.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425068/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425068/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Business: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish his Department's Business Tax Roadmap.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425069","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>The Government continues to track the status of nationally significant infrastructure projects and programmes in the National Infrastructure Pipeline, which underpins the National Infrastructure Plan. In July 2015, the Government published a refresh of the National Infrastructure Pipeline containing details on the status of UK infrastructure projects.</p><p>Over 2,650 projects were completed in the last Parliament and a number of priority projects have been completed since the last National Infrastructure Plan was published, including Manchester Victoria station and Nottingham Express Transit Phase 2.</p><p><br> <br> <br></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-04T15:40:05.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425069/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425069/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish an update on the delivery of the National Infrastructure Plan.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425070","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>The independent review of UK economic statistics will publish interim recommendations for the Chancellor of the Exchequer and the Minister for the Cabinet Office in autumn 2015. A final report will be published at Budget 2016.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-11-04T10:48:20.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425070/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425070/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","UK Economic Statistics Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish the interim recommendations of Sir Charles Bean's review of the quality, delivery and governance of local statistics.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425071","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>I refer the member to the answer I provided on 30 October 2015 to question 13346:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=13346" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=13346</a></p><br />","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-11-04T13:01:45.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425071/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425071/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department allocated to pay staff of HM Revenue and Customs to deal with enquiries from hon. Members relating to constituents' concerns about tax credits in (a) 2015-16 and (b) each of the three previous years.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","14225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425072","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>On 5<sup>th</sup> October we announced plans to reform business rates in England, a change that will see local government retaining all revenue for the first time since 1990. The new powers will come with new responsibilities and the phasing out of grants from Whitehall to ensure that the reforms are fiscally neutral. Over the course of the next eighteen months we will be working with local government on the details of the scheme. Ahead of final decisions, it is too early to assess what the impact will be on individual areas.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-04T15:56:06.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425072/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425072/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Non-domestic Rates: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the effect on revenue to the Exchequer of allowing devolved local authorities to keep 100 per cent of the business rates raised from car parks in (a) the UK, (b) England and (c) Wiltshire in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","14260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425073","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-09","<p>Earnings from UK overseas assets are below.</p><p>Year Earnings From Overseas Assets<br>(£bn)<br>1985 50.1<br>1986 45.5<br>1987 46.4<br>1988 54.6<br>1989 71.7<br>1990 76.5<br>1991 73.9<br>1992 65.4<br>1993 71.2<br>1994 72.9<br>1995 85.8<br>1996 90.1<br>1997 96.2<br>1998 105.9<br>1999 103.4<br>2000 134.5<br>2001 139.9<br>2002 124.2<br>2003 124.9<br>2004 140.9<br>2005 193.0<br>2006 249.3<br>2007 307.9<br>2008 287.9<br>2009 175.1<br>2010 174.0<br>2011 200.0<br>2012 170.4<br>2013 148.5<br>2014 141.1</p><p>Further information can be found in the ONS UK Balance of Payments.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-09T16:18:09.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425073/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Overseas Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the earnings from UK overseas assets were in each of the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","14215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425074","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-09","<p>The latest forecasts by the Office of Budget Responsibility show that the UK’s net investment income is expected to move to a surplus of £0.5bn in 2018, rising to £4.9bn by 2020.</p><br /><p>Further information can be found in the OBR Economic and Fiscal Outlook.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-09T16:11:10.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425074/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425074/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Overseas Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the likely level of earnings from UK overseas assets over the next 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","14214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425075","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>Our long term economic plan is working, with the UK growing faster than any other major economy in 2013 and 14. But job is not done, which is why we are working with industry to drive innovation and lead the global race in technology, engineering and manufacturing.</p><br /><p>To encourage investment in manufacturing and the economy as a whole, the Government has announced an increase in the permanent level of Annual Investment Allowance (AIA) from £25,000 to £200,000 from 1 January 2016. This incentivises investment in plant and machinery, and SMEs will benefit disproportionately.</p><br /><p>Catapult centres are further supporting the UK’s manufacturing productivity and competitiveness, facilitating collaboration and boosting inward investment. £300m has been invested in manufacturing through the High Value Manufacturing Catapult network and over the last year it has worked with over 1,650 private sector clients on over 1,300 projects.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-11-04T12:39:09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425075/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425075/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-30","Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to encourage manufacturing.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","14171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425076","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-04","<p>The design and management of streets and pavements is the responsibility of local authorities. We expect local authorities to work towards high quality, attractive and inclusive streets that work for all people including wheelchairs users.</p><br /><p>This Government is committed to promoting an inclusive transport system and there is a range of national guidance on street design issues in Department for Transport documents and elsewhere to assist local authorities considering the design of streets for wheelchair users. Best practice is set out in the Inclusive Mobility guidance which we plan to update next year <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3695/inclusive-mobility.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3695/inclusive-mobility.pdf</a>.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-11-04T17:16:27.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425076/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425076/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-30","Pedestrian Areas: Wheelchairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will improve access to pavements for wheelchair users.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","14207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425077","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-05","<p>By2017, approximately 95 per cent of homes and businesses in Northamptonshire will have access to superfast broadband. To support further delivery, a further £1.9 million of funding has been made available through the contractual gainshare arrangements, and Northamptonshire County Council has further funding available beyond this for additional procurement.</p><p><br>In addition, the Government is supporting seven pilot projects to help deliver superfast broadband services to the hardest to reach parts of the UK. We will publish the findings from the pilots in duecourse.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-11-05T10:54:49.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425077/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425077/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-30","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to ensure the delivery of superfast broadband to the remaining five per cent of properties which do not have access to it in (a) Northamptonshire and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","14263"
